===Etymology===
Named after German chemist {{w|Emil Erlenmeyer}}, who invented it in 1861.

===Noun===
{{en-noun}}

# {{lb|en|chemistry}} A glass [[laboratory]] flask of a conical profile with a narrow tubular neck and a flat bottom, used to manipulate solutions or carry out [[titration]]s.
#* '''2006''', Thomas Pynchon, ''Against the Day'', Vintage 2007, p. 265:
#*: An assistant arrived with a wheeled cart bearing coffee in an '''Erlenmeyer flask''', cups, and a plate of strange muffins.

